		<header>
			
			<h1>Pescanova: ‘Six months of scandal at stricken giant’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Pescanova filed for insolvency 6 months ago, and the online magazine <i>Undercurrent News</i> is dedicating a special spotlight page for the occasion, taking a look back over the key events of the last 6 months.</p><p><i>Undercurrent News</i> recalls that before the event, Pescanova was lauded as an example of successful vertical integration, controlling the supply chain from fishing vessels and aquaculture operations around the world, to retailers selling Pescanova brand products. However, “this empire has subsequently been revealed to have been built on fraud, with the company’s real debt pinned at €3.6 billion.”</p><p>Pescanova has more than 80 branches worldwide, including in Mozambique (Pescamar, Pescabom, Efripel), Namibia (Novanam), Angola (Novapesca), South Africa (Novagroup), Chile (Pesca Chile), and Argentina (Argenova).</p><p>Currently, Pescafina – the largest subsidiary of Pescanova, which acts as a sales point for Pescanova seafood from around the globe, including products coming from Namibia and Mozambique – is also threatened by bankruptcy.</p><p>At the beginning of the “Pescanova affair”, Novanam – Pescanova’s Namibian hake fishing and processing subsidiary – claimed that the insolvency process Pescanova was going through “wouldn’t impact its business”. In early June, however, <i>El Economista</i> revealed that Pescanova hid its massive debt across an “opaque network of companies”. Pescanova’s Namibian subsidiary, Novanam, could be particularly indebted, owing more than €400 million.</p><p>According to Pescanova’s reorganisation report, the only measure that the company can take is to agree with creditor banks to refinance its debt. In addition, “its non-strategic businesses can be sold and capitalized to plug an asset hole amounting to a further €1,667 million,” reported <i>La Opinión</i>. Later on, sources reported in <i>La Opinión</i> suggested that Pacific Andes, one of the world’s biggest seafood groups, was interested in acquiring Novanam.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Undercurrentnews.com</i>, ‘Six months of scandal at stricken giant’, spotlight page on Pescanova, 9&nbsp;September 2013</p><p class=" text-left">
<a href="http://www.undercurrentnews.com/2013/09/09/pescanova-six-months-of-scandal-at-stricken-seafood-giant/?utm_source=wysija&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=europe_newsletter_sept_9#.Ui2G3aRV3IU" target="_self">http://www.undercurrentnews.com/2013/09/09/pescanova-six-months-of-scand...</a></p><p><i>Europapress.es</i>, ‘Deloitte valora entre 85 y 100 millones la marca Pescanova, menos de la mitad de lo atribuido por la empresa’, 6&nbsp;September 2013</p><p class=" text-left">
<a href="http://www.europapress.es/galicia/noticia-deloitte-valora-85-100-millones-marca-pescanova-menos-mitad-atribuido-empresa-20130906185810.html" target="_self">http://www.europapress.es/galicia/noticia-deloitte-valora-85-100-millone...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Many ACP countries are offering attractive conditions for foreign companies to invest in their fisheries: low taxes, fisheries’ access rights, etc. However, as is shown by the Pescanova fate, these investments may not be sufficiently protected should the foreign company encounter difficulties. In the case of EU-based companies, since the entry into force of the Lisbon Treaty in 2010, the “protection of investments” has become an EU prerogative. It may be advisable for ACP countries to insist this issue is taken up in regional dialogues, in a way that the EU investors’ operations made in ACP fisheries are fully transparent – to avoid them “hiding their debts” in their ACP subsidiaries – and that activities generated by these investments receive some kind of protection.</p>
		</div>
		
